<font color="#FF0000">SURVIVING JUST AND UNJUST WARS</font><br>
<tt>Thu May 29 21:24:34 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I was reading through some of the older posts on this topic and was struck by Heather Hansmann (12/12/96) and Arthur Varanelli (12/11/96) and their discussions of the Haunting War and the Multi-level understanding. I teach a great deal about the effects of surviving violence and being a perpetrator of violence. It seems that perpetrators of violence, especially those who would not do violence to another under normal circumstances but who are forced or decide to do so in war always suffer consequences. Having talked a great deal with WWII veterans it seems that participation in a &quot;Just war&quot; had its ocnsequences. Sometimes it seems that the consequences run very deep. Within the &quot;just war&quot; framework it becomes very difficult to reject behavior one knows is wrong, killing others, even enemies, even when one feels the cause is right. With warm receptions at home, with victory, with being called heros, many WWII veterans never seem to have had the opportunity to reject openly, talk about and confront what many felt as the horrors of war. Any war. I happened to watch the old 1930's &quot;All Quiet on the Western Front&quot; the other night and war was hell just or not. I remember watching my father who spent time in Italy and Africa during WWII watching WWII films or meeting with old Army buddies. Ass a child it alwaysseemed that he was incredibly quiet. Taking part but always on the periphery. The discussions of these ex-soldiers always seemed superficial and off the point, but reflected an underlying wealth of feelings and reactios which men of that war and time were somehow never able to openly acknowledge. To do so would possibly free them from some of their hauntings, but it would also destroy the images family and friends and other citizens created of those who faught in WWII. <br><br>
Arthur Varanelli is certainly correct in his observations about the need for a multi-level unnderstanding of Viet Nam. But I wonder if a multi-level understanding of the effects of all wars should also be considered. Watching the Memorial Day concert from Washington D.C. this year, the journey through many wars and the recognition of the WWI veterans surviving really made me think of this.
